R Markdown Report for analysis of developing gut microbiome in infants en route to type 1 diabetes (TID)

Raymond Atuhe, Reg No: 2020/HDO7/22160U, Student Number: 2000722160

25 06 2021

Background

This is an R markdown script explaining and running analysis of developing gut microbiome in infants en route to type 1 diabetes (TID). The data is based on two Bioconductor packages; phyloseq and DEseq2. It was given as an assignemnt in completion of a masters Degree in Bioinformatics.

## 
## Attaching package: 'kableExtra'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     group_rows

Load necessary libraries

library("phyloseq")
library("ggplot2")      # graphics
library("readxl")       # necessary to import the data from Excel file
library("dplyr")        # filter and reformat data frames
library("tibble")       # Needed for converting column to row names
library("readr")        #read Rectangular Text data
library("DESeq2")       #Needed to normalize, visualize, and differential analysis if high dimensional data
library("table1")       #Tables of Descriptive statistics
library("tidyverse")

1. Importing the data described below into R and providing Descriptive statistics

All data files should be in the same working folder for easy analysis.
I was given 2 data files; i.e. * diabimmune_16s_t1d_metadata.csv * diabimmune_t1d_16s_otu_table.txt

The second data file was given as a text delimited file(.txt), and contained both the Taxonomic Units and Abundances.

For better analysis i had to separate diabimmune_t1d_16s_otu_table.txt to get OTUs and Taxonomy’s from the Terminal.

The .csv file was read into R by importing it directly as below.

#Importing sample data into R.
metadata <- read.csv("diabimmune_16s_t1d_metadata.csv")

Appropriate Graphics on the subject data

  • Defining objects to use in visualizations.
Gender <- metadata$Gender
Age_at_Collection <- metadata$Age_at_Collection
Delivery_Route <- metadata$Delivery_Route
Case_Control <- as.factor(metadata$Case_Control)
plot_colours <- ifelse(levels(Case_Control)=="case", rgb(0.1,0.1,0.7,0.5),
                   ifelse(levels(Case_Control)=="control", "red", rgb(0.8,0.1,0.3,0.6) ))

Boxplot

Basic Boxplot of Disease Status vs Age

boxplot(Age_at_Collection~ Case_Control, main="Boxplot determining Case Controls against Age at Collection", xlab="Case Control", ylab="Age at Collection", col=plot_colours)

#### Bar Graph. Basic Bar graph repesenting precenatges of Gender by Delivery Route

#ggplot graphs 
ggplot(metadata, aes(x = Gender ,y= (..count..)/sum(..count..), fill= Delivery_Route)) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge", color= "Black")+
  scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent)+ 
  labs(title = "Percentage of Gender by Delivery Route", y= "Percentage", x= "Gender" )+
  geom_text(stat= "count", aes(label= scales::percent((..count..)/sum(..count..))), position = position_dodge(0.9), size=4, vjust=-0.1)+
  theme_classic()+ scale_fill_manual(name = "", values = c("red", "blue"))

Association Tests between Case Control and Gender

Fisher’s Exact Test for Count Data

fisher.test(Case_Control, Gender)

2. creating a phyloseq object. This comprises of the OTU abundance, taxonomy and sample data (provided in the .csv file).

To create a phyloseq object, I Imported data into R. * All files are in my working directory to where the they are located * Three tables are required * OTU abundance * Taxonomy * sample data

# Importing OTU abundance table
OTU_Table <- read.table("otu_table")

# Importing Taxonomy table
Taxa_Table <- read.table("new_taxa_table")

Differential abundance using DESeq2

Converting the phloseq object to DESeq2 and then caling and viewing the results.

OTU_matrix1 <-  OTU_mat+1
OTU1 <- otu_table(OTU_matrix1, taxa_are_rows = TRUE)
deseq_object <- phyloseq(OTU1, TAX, Samples)
TID_ds <- phyloseq_to_deseq2(deseq_object, ~ Case_Control)
## converting counts to integer mode
